nocence explores the political dynamics that have shaped the proliferation of innocence-related policies across the United States and the ways in which wrongful convictions affect public opinion about the criminal legal system. Although some have suggested that this issue transcends ideological divisions, the authors argue that public opinion and the policies that address wrongful convictions are a product of the political landscape. Using original data, the authors show how political ideology influences awareness of the issue, affects support for policy reform, and, in particular electoral contexts, influences state policy adoption. The Politics of Innocence is a moving and data-driven account of wrongful convictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aJudicial errorzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aconservative.  acriminal justice system.  acriminal justice.  adue process.  aevidence preservation.  aexonerated.  aexonerees.  aframing.  aincarcerated.  ainnocence movement.  ainnocence organizations.  aliberal.  anews media.  anews.  apodcasts.  apolice interrogation.  apolitical interests.  apublic opinion.  astate policy.  awrongful conviction.1 aHicks, William D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMullinix, Kevin J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479816033.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479816033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479816033/original  a978-3-11-075163-5  New York University Press Complete eBook-